1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:07,220
So, I visited some electronics stores and here's what I managed to pick up.

2
00:00:09,940 --> 00:00:17,190
The switch I showed you — I got it a while back, its price with the handle was 100 rubles.

3
00:00:19,300 --> 00:00:29,460
A small ring for the current sensor — ferrite with permeability 2200, with an outer diameter.

4
00:00:31,340 --> 00:00:37,960
Of 23 mm, costs 80 rubles.

5
00:00:40,740 --> 00:00:54,340
A 40-amp relay — here's the marking with four outputs — costs 120 rubles.

6
00:00:54,340 --> 00:01:02,410
And the converter I made for power.

7
00:01:02,910 --> 00:01:09,590
Total cost of the parts was 500 rubles, maybe slightly less.

8
00:01:10,390 --> 00:01:15,550
In particular, the core for this converter came to 200 rubles.

9
00:01:16,470 --> 00:01:21,670
And the prototyping board another hundred — that's already 300, and the rest is in parts.

10
00:01:26,210 --> 00:01:35,870
A board — this kind of double-sided board, nothing fancy — 250 rubles.

11
00:01:36,490 --> 00:01:40,670
The PWM controller will be mounted on it.

12
00:01:43,670 --> 00:01:44,330
Switches.

13
00:01:44,630 --> 00:01:50,230
For the switches I took IRFP-064N.

14
00:01:52,670 --> 00:01:53,690
Here they are.

15
00:01:55,650 --> 00:01:59,830
The cost of one switch is 100 rubles.

16
00:02:07,150 --> 00:02:16,450
Further — I pulled this core for the pulse transformer.

17
00:02:18,630 --> 00:02:24,930
Available were ones with 63 mm outer size.

18
00:02:28,330 --> 00:02:31,570
Inner 37 mm.

19
00:02:36,250 --> 00:02:40,630
25.5 mm width.

20
00:02:41,030 --> 00:02:48,110
Wall thickness 13 mm.

21
00:02:49,990 --> 00:02:51,190
500 rubles.

22
00:02:53,490 --> 00:02:58,550
Besides this, I picked a heat sink.

23
00:02:59,870 --> 00:03:08,190
The plan is for the system to work without airflow, so I took a bigger heat sink for the power switches.

24
00:03:08,430 --> 00:03:10,430
Its cost — 150 rubles.

25
00:03:13,810 --> 00:03:20,430
The PWM controller itself will be built on a UC3825N chip.

26
00:03:21,950 --> 00:03:24,610
Cost of the chip — 85 rubles.

27
00:03:26,370 --> 00:03:30,430
Four HCPL3120 opto-drivers.

28
00:03:31,670 --> 00:03:34,190
Cost per piece — 120 rubles.

29
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:48,760
And I picked a box sized so everything would look nice.

30
00:03:49,440 --> 00:03:51,800
Cost of the box — 190 rubles.

31
00:03:53,280 --> 00:03:54,560
Interesting thing.

32
00:03:56,760 --> 00:03:58,460
This is what it looks like.

33
00:04:01,020 --> 00:04:03,580
Cover fits tightly.

34
00:04:04,520 --> 00:04:09,380
Comes with self-tapping screws and plugs.

35
00:04:09,400 --> 00:04:12,840
For these holes.

36
00:04:14,240 --> 00:04:21,900
Sturdy plastic and very pleasing to see the marking on the inner part.

37
00:04:23,440 --> 00:04:31,520
You won't have to apply it yourself — you can already make holes for the wire passage according to it.

38
00:04:34,820 --> 00:04:36,180
Nice thing.

39
00:04:36,180 --> 00:04:43,680
Besides this I also took these mounting standoffs that are sold here.

40
00:04:47,260 --> 00:04:50,920
Useful, for example, for installing the heat sink.

41
00:04:52,620 --> 00:04:58,720
20 mm long, cost 15 rubles.

42
00:04:59,060 --> 00:05:05,560
10 mm short ones, cost 10 rubles each.

43
00:05:12,280 --> 00:05:21,680
Total — today's costs on this build came to 2955 rubles.

44
00:05:22,580 --> 00:05:24,960
That's everything shown here.

45
00:05:26,020 --> 00:05:29,700
As always, I didn't manage without extra expenses.

46
00:05:31,040 --> 00:05:37,700
I bought this PTFE film at one of the stores.

47
00:05:38,760 --> 00:05:43,760
Insulation we'll use to wrap our high-voltage core.

48
00:05:45,120 --> 00:05:51,440
Managed to buy this Soviet-era roll.

49
00:05:51,880 --> 00:05:56,880
You can see the GOST stamp — 500 rubles.

50
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:59,360
Will last me a long time.

51
00:06:00,740 --> 00:06:07,160
And besides this, I bought these interesting screwdrivers.

52
00:06:07,700 --> 00:06:09,600
The kit cost 800 rubles.

53
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:12,460
Really like the set.

54
00:06:14,640 --> 00:06:18,140
Various types of bits.

55
00:06:18,280 --> 00:06:21,740
Pretty thin, made neatly.

56
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:26,380
Plus sockets for small nuts.

57
00:06:26,880 --> 00:06:29,920
Just what you need for fastening.

58
00:06:31,440 --> 00:06:34,880
The screwdriver itself opens.

59
00:06:36,140 --> 00:06:40,080
I pulled this core from it.

60
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,140
Flipping it over — it's faceted.

61
00:06:44,020 --> 00:06:48,240
And inside, along the length of the plastic tube, it's also faceted.

62
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:51,820
And this part only serves as a fixator.

63
00:06:51,820 --> 00:06:57,500
The force is transmitted through the facet along the length of the screwdriver.

64
00:07:01,290 --> 00:07:10,570
And of course I couldn't avoid buying various resistor kits and other things.

65
00:07:12,410 --> 00:07:15,190
It worked out — I shopped well today.

66
00:07:16,390 --> 00:07:17,890
About 8000 rubles.

67
00:07:19,090 --> 00:07:23,110
Hope my wife won't watch this video.

68
00:07:25,290 --> 00:07:29,110
And now we can move to the build.

69
00:07:30,250 --> 00:07:31,550
So, where to start.

70
00:07:31,810 --> 00:07:39,010
With about the same operation I did in the store, when I picked the box for this.

71
00:07:40,310 --> 00:07:41,870
Box dimensions for us.

72
00:07:41,870 --> 00:07:48,950
Length 15.7 cm.

73
00:07:52,270 --> 00:07:55,690
Thickness 5.3 cm.

74
00:07:57,010 --> 00:08:01,630
And width 9.5 cm.

75
00:08:03,810 --> 00:08:09,710
In the store I planned how all the parts would be placed here.

76
00:08:09,710 --> 00:08:14,810
So I took this switch and converter with me.

77
00:08:14,950 --> 00:08:16,430
So I could lay it out.

78
00:08:17,190 --> 00:08:20,890
And here's roughly the layout we'll have.

79
00:08:22,430 --> 00:08:23,370
Heat sink.

80
00:08:23,830 --> 00:08:31,850
The heat sink is 6.3 cm wide.

81
00:08:33,090 --> 00:08:35,060
Length 10 cm.

82
00:08:35,060 --> 00:08:42,600
And rib thickness 3.3 cm.

83
00:08:43,580 --> 00:08:46,420
These are the dimensions we care about.

84
00:08:47,500 --> 00:08:53,480
The switches will be placed like this on this heat sink.

85
00:08:55,840 --> 00:09:05,040
If you place them exactly this way, it's very convenient to make connections for the midpoints.

86
00:09:05,060 --> 00:09:11,280
That's the source of one transistor connected to the drain of another.

87
00:09:12,840 --> 00:09:19,640
It's convenient that these leads can be bent up and you connect to them.

88
00:09:20,200 --> 00:09:27,470
And it's also convenient to bring power to the switches with this layout.

89
00:09:27,740 --> 00:09:30,120
That is, by plus and by minus.

90
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:32,400
Middle leads.

91
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:38,820
This connects two switches by plus.

92
00:09:40,380 --> 00:09:42,600
Bend up, pass a wire.

93
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:53,920
And the lead far right, counting left to right, in this pair will be connected to minus.

94
00:09:56,700 --> 00:10:02,640
I also picked the board so it would fit in this box.

95
00:10:02,900 --> 00:10:08,940
And it fits very conveniently — the board clearly goes in here.

96
00:10:09,340 --> 00:10:17,960
You can see it doesn't even move thanks to two stop strips.

97
00:10:19,620 --> 00:10:33,080
The idea is that the leads from the transistors will pass through this plastic and exit directly into the board.

98
00:10:33,220 --> 00:10:38,840
This way we fulfill the rules for power electronics.

99
00:10:39,400 --> 00:10:44,720
The drivers will be located as close as possible to the switches.

100
00:10:45,510 --> 00:10:52,180
To minimize pickup on them and make for quality control.

101
00:10:52,900 --> 00:10:56,600
So you need to calculate the transistor placement accordingly.

102
00:10:57,720 --> 00:11:04,040
Here roughly — if you look — their leads exit at these points.

103
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:14,700
And there's enough distance below them to place the optical drivers in the corners of the board.

104
00:11:16,520 --> 00:11:18,580
I plan to do it this way.

105
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:22,980
The drivers themselves will go in the corners.

106
00:11:23,900 --> 00:11:28,700
And before them the transistor legs come out.

107
00:11:28,860 --> 00:11:31,460
Both the drain and the gate before each driver.

108
00:11:31,580 --> 00:11:33,800
The zener diodes will also go here.

109
00:11:34,480 --> 00:11:37,100
A resistor discharge chain.

110
00:11:38,140 --> 00:11:39,540
Limiting resistor.

111
00:11:39,720 --> 00:11:42,420
That is, calculating roughly so it's convenient.

112
00:11:42,420 --> 00:11:50,220
And the PWM controller board itself — that is, the controller chip — will be in the middle.

113
00:11:51,540 --> 00:11:56,240
And the support components to the left and right of it.

114
00:11:57,280 --> 00:12:00,460
The necessary RC chains for its operation.

115
00:12:05,390 --> 00:12:09,290
Now about the inner part.

116
00:12:10,930 --> 00:12:14,290
Inside, the switch fits.

117
00:12:15,130 --> 00:12:20,770
By dimensions I checked that it fits, if you bring its handle out from this side.

118
00:12:22,590 --> 00:12:24,230
That's how it'll be placed.

119
00:12:24,390 --> 00:12:26,150
Here are its dimensions.

120
00:12:26,490 --> 00:12:29,790
It fits by height — hides nicely.

121
00:12:30,770 --> 00:12:39,350
Now the power converter will be placed like this.

122
00:12:40,390 --> 00:12:45,470
You can clearly see that when the switch is in place, it won't interfere with it.

123
00:12:46,090 --> 00:12:49,150
Further — the relay will go here.

124
00:12:52,200 --> 00:12:58,070
And here, at this point, will be the board.

125
00:12:59,270 --> 00:13:03,410
It'll be placed like this.

126
00:13:04,090 --> 00:13:06,250
But there's still space under it.

127
00:13:06,250 --> 00:13:13,530
I think I'll allocate this space to the output part.

128
00:13:14,650 --> 00:13:19,610
For the diode bridge and caps, plus the smoothing choke.

129
00:13:19,910 --> 00:13:21,690
There's enough space.

130
00:13:22,570 --> 00:13:26,850
Turns out the transformer doesn't fit in the box.

131
00:13:28,530 --> 00:13:34,570
So I decided to place it on top of the build.

132
00:13:39,270 --> 00:13:42,310
The heat sink with the switches will be located like this.

133
00:13:45,270 --> 00:13:48,550
And the power transformer goes here.

134
00:13:50,710 --> 00:13:55,430
I believe, if you wind it nicely, it'll be quite cute.

135
00:13:55,530 --> 00:13:56,870
That's the build.

136
00:13:56,970 --> 00:13:59,270
Power wires will come out here.

137
00:14:00,270 --> 00:14:01,530
The output will also be here.

138
00:14:02,470 --> 00:14:06,570
The switch is on this side for easy switching.

139
00:14:07,390 --> 00:14:18,850
And the variable resistors at convenient places.

140
00:14:19,050 --> 00:14:26,990
For pulse duration regulation and current protection trip regulation.

141
00:14:27,770 --> 00:14:30,650
Somewhere here.

142
00:14:30,750 --> 00:14:33,110
We'll see by dimensions where it'll be convenient.

143
00:14:33,910 --> 00:14:35,430
That's the plan.

144
00:14:36,030 --> 00:14:38,210
Now we can move to assembly.

145
00:14:39,690 --> 00:14:48,430
I start the assembly with applying markings, dimensions, parts.

146
00:14:50,470 --> 00:15:00,650
We need to position the power switches according to the marking.

147
00:15:02,590 --> 00:15:08,620
So their leads match the holes on the prototyping board.

148
00:15:12,470 --> 00:15:17,150
Any neat work starts with marking, which I did.

149
00:15:17,150 --> 00:15:24,390
For this I transferred the heat sink dimensions to the inner surface of the top cover.

150
00:15:25,670 --> 00:15:30,990
And per these dimensions installed the prototyping board.

151
00:15:32,690 --> 00:15:42,550
I decided to make the factory mounting holes in the prototyping board the fastenings for the heat sink.

152
00:15:42,550 --> 00:15:48,810
For this I drilled holes in the top cover.

153
00:15:49,690 --> 00:15:54,830
And after that I transferred them to the heat sink surface.

154
00:15:55,650 --> 00:16:02,290
If you look, they clearly correspond to these four points.

155
00:16:03,150 --> 00:16:12,050
I'll thread mounting standoffs into these points after cutting threads in advance.

156
00:16:13,590 --> 00:16:16,830
Which were acquired in advance.

157
00:16:18,730 --> 00:16:29,390
And this way the heat sink will be fixed to the surface of the plastic cover.

158
00:16:30,270 --> 00:16:40,070
By the way, I recommend drilling and cutting threads in aluminum together with WD-40.

159
00:16:40,070 --> 00:16:43,290
The tap goes smoothly without chips and seizures.

160
00:16:43,450 --> 00:16:47,550
Otherwise you risk breaking small drills.

161
00:16:47,990 --> 00:16:55,750
And worse — the tap may get stuck and removing it will be practically impossible.

162
00:17:00,990 --> 00:17:06,350
Next, I formed the FET transistor leads.

163
00:17:06,350 --> 00:17:15,670
You can see I extended the gate and source leads with copper wire.

164
00:17:17,030 --> 00:17:28,030
The leads through which minus power will be supplied are bent in a ring, with wire threaded through.

165
00:17:28,030 --> 00:17:38,970
And the switch that'll get plus power has the same treatment done on the middle lead.

166
00:17:39,750 --> 00:17:52,190
By extending these wires, I can freely thread them through the plastic cover.

167
00:17:52,190 --> 00:18:00,630
Through these holes that matched by dimensions with the marking on the cover.

168
00:18:01,410 --> 00:18:15,210
And you can see that on the board I already outlined the points with a marker — these are the exit points of the extended switch legs.

169
00:18:17,390 --> 00:18:32,270
To transfer this picture to the heat sink surface, I installed the cover on its top.

170
00:18:32,450 --> 00:18:34,870
This was done without mounting standoffs.

171
00:18:34,950 --> 00:18:38,930
Fixed in these holes with bolts.

172
00:18:38,930 --> 00:18:49,050
And only after this did I make marks for drilling holes and for switch fastening.

173
00:18:51,570 --> 00:18:56,030
The work isn't hard, but it requires care.

174
00:18:57,510 --> 00:19:05,390
Now we can move to building the power module.

175
00:19:06,390 --> 00:19:12,290
We won't manage to make the power module today, we'll deal with it tomorrow.

176
00:19:13,530 --> 00:19:21,210
At the end of this video we can assemble it preliminarily — see what we get,

177
00:19:24,810 --> 00:19:28,610
how the build will look.

178
00:19:29,690 --> 00:19:36,690
For this we fix the heat sink with mounting standoffs.

179
00:19:42,100 --> 00:19:47,760
It'll be solidly fixed on the surface.

180
00:19:51,100 --> 00:20:01,900
Also placed the board on the following mounting standoffs.

181
00:20:05,100 --> 00:20:09,000
The screwdriver I just bought comes in handy.

182
00:20:22,480 --> 00:20:24,300
That's how this thing looks.

183
00:20:27,730 --> 00:20:31,510
A pretty solid build.

184
00:20:39,630 --> 00:20:41,850
That's all for now.

185
00:20:43,150 --> 00:20:44,510
Good mood.

186
00:20:45,430 --> 00:20:46,790
Wait for the next video.
